    sidingMaterialPara: "Brick veneer dominates Charlotte at roughly 60 percent of residential stock, driven by the Piedmont's deep red-clay soils that historically supplied local brick kilns. James Hardie fiber cement covers post-2000 tract construction across the Ballantyne-Waxhaw-Fort Mill suburban ring. Wood clapboard survives on 1920s-1940s craftsman bungalows in Dilworth, Plaza Midwood, and NoDa, requiring periodic scraping and priming against tannin bleed. Stucco appears on a handful of Mediterranean-revival homes in Myers Park and Eastover but is far less common than in Atlanta or Tampa. Board-and-batten cedar accents on Lake Norman waterfront custom builds are a Charlotte-specific luxury aesthetic.",
